title.narrative: ALTERNATIVE EDUCATION

description.narrative: Partners have capacity to provide children/adolescent aged 3-18 with alternative education at primary and lower secondary levels, and continuous learning for children in emergencies., which contributes to Access To Quality Learning Opportunities, Access To Quality Learning Opportunities (Covid), Evaluation, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Operations Support To Programme Delivery, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Research. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, children, especially the most disadvantaged, will acquire knowledge and skills in an inclusive, safe, quality learning environment to complete pre-primary, primary, transit to secondary and complete lower secondary education

title.narrative: Partners have capacity to provide children/adolescent aged 3-18 with alternative education at primary and lower secondary levels,and continuous learning for children in emergencies.

description.narrative: Number of school children without learning opportunities increased significantly due to the double-edged crisis caused by COVID-19 and the military takeover. Despite a number of challenges, UNICEF Education continued to work with civil society partners across the country to support children’s continuous learning. ;A total of 77,758 children were supported with pre-primary, primary and post primary education in conflict affected states. ;An additional 4,044 adolescents were supported through alternative education programming. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:14/01/2022
